      <div>
        <div class="tr-read-label">📖 Read This First</div>
        <div class="tr-read-block">
          <div class="tr-read-section">Why reviews are the most powerful ranking signal</div>
          <p>Review count and average rating are in Google's top five local ranking factors. A business with 50 four-star reviews will outrank a business with 5 five-star reviews almost every time. Volume beats perfection.</p>
          <div class="tr-read-section" style="margin-top:12px;">The review card system</div>
          <p>The review card removes all friction. One scan and the customer is on the review page. Use the Review Card Maker to build it for every new client. Brief them: hand it or WhatsApp a photo the same day as the job. Say it out loud. That verbal ask is the difference between a review that happens and one that doesn't.</p>
          <div class="tr-read-section" style="margin-top:12px;">What to avoid</div>
          <p>Never incentivise reviews — Google's terms explicitly prohibit it and profiles get suspended. Never ask for reviews in bulk — a sudden spike of 15 reviews in a week looks fake to Google and often gets filtered. The right pace is 1–3 per week consistently.</p>
          <div class="tr-read-section" style="margin-top:12px;">Negative reviews</div>
          <p>One professionally handled negative review can do more for trust than ten positives. The formula: acknowledge, do not argue, apologise for the experience (not the error), invite them offline. Never get defensive. The audience is not the reviewer — it is every future customer reading the response.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
